summary: I’ve heard a lot of people talk about creepy things that are in the Pokemon games, from the XY elevator person to Lavender Town,...
body:
I’ve heard a lot of people talk about creepy things that are in the Pokemon games, from the XY elevator person to Lavender Town, but I don’t really hear that much about the one NPC in Black and White 2′s Lostlorn Forest that talks to you about how most of the forest was a Zoroark’s illusion, gives you a TM, and then turns into a Zoroark and runs away.

It wasn’t the creepiest thing in the games, but it sure was creepy to stumble upon without any warning.

summary: I'd love to hear some stories on Manaphy please!
question: I'd love to hear some stories on Manaphy please!
answer:
I don’t think I have the energy to do full-length synopses and reviews anymore, unfortunately. However, here are some small Manaphy myths!

Nicolas le Poisson (Nicholas the Fish) is the story of a boy who loved swimming so much that his mother tells him he would become a fish sooner or later, and her words cause him to become half-fish. He dives and tells everyone about the wonderful things he saw, until one day the king shows up and tells him to dive to the bottom of the sea in one specific area which is so deep that Nicolas has never even seen the bottom. Nicolas refuses, so the king removes his crown and throws it into the water; Nicolas swims after it, and as he swims deeper, he changes further until he becomes a manaphy. He is never seen again, but supposedly he returns home to see his family whenever there is a total lunar eclipse.

L’homme qui est Tombé Amoureux de la Lune (The Man who Fell in Love with the Moon) is about a man who, as the title would imply, falls in love with the moon. He pines away and eventually becomes extremely sick, and begs his family to take him to the water’s edge, where he rages at the tides for being connected to the moon’s movement. The moon (not explicitly named as Cresselia, but implied to be such) takes pity on him and makes him a manaphy so that he can wash away with the tides. 

There are several myths in which children “go to the water” or are taken by a parent who cannot or will not care for them, and who are rescued by Manaphy and taken to live inside its temple.

summary: Facetoad, The Diamond Pokémon  The name is a combination of facet like the faces of a diamond and toad.  Type - Rock  Height -...
caption:
Facetoad, The Diamond Pokémon

The name is a combination of facet like the faces of a diamond and toad.

Type - Rock
Height - 3'1"
Weight - 86 lbs.
Ability - Rock Head/ Sturdy
Pokédex Entry - For many years, this Pokémon was sought for the luxurious gems that grow from its body. Now it is quite rare.

This Pokémon evolves from Koalfrog when it is placed under pressure… which means it must win a battle with only 1HP.
